The architects took a look - the office also includes a kindergarten
The office building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything included: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
From the first designs for the new building Avriopoint, the Arch.Design design and architecture office, from whose studios a number of well-known Brno buildings originate, counted on the premises for its company mini kindergarten.
Most of his 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is concerned that the project managers and architects return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Along with the possibility of working shortly, kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for civil engineers to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The mini kindergarten is an original idea of the Arch.Design employees and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company mini kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from funds of the European Social Fund and from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (subsidies of CZK 2.8 million), the necessary facilities and equipment were obtained and for a period of 2 years qualified personnel and operations were provided.
After the use of the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue to operate the mini kindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the processing of the application.
The children are taken care of all-day qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can be visited by children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but several children alternate the day with each other.
The kindergarten operation is flexibly tailored to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights with regard to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective positions.
Although it is about individual education and nursing, the programme content in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the supporting programme of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all, they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool lessons, besides, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to the children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time, eliminating the stress of late picking up the children from a distant kindergarten.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships also emerge here.
Arch.Design thus ranked among the Czech companies that offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was nicknamed "bone house".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, the dandruff-reminiscent facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living things.
It is only on closer inspection that one notices that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole façade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special lighting enhances the gloss of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and twisted shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even lookouts and strips.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia no. 43 was created by the renovation of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese carried out.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of an entirely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí’s idea of an unusual and also cheaper renovation.
However, the Casa Batlló building was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was precisely on its drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner were created and the use of mosaics on the facade was also his idea.
However, numerous other painters and artists also worked on the design of the facade.
Working together on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí’s Casa Milá in the Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed "bone house" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the " yawning house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
But also other sculptural elements symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system unique to the time with vent ducts and typical fireplaces.
Something bizarre seems to be their 45-degree inclination.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building codes of the time and was not impressed by them.
Before the start of construction, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, the city fathers were so horrified by the result that they demanded remedy.
Among other things, the councillors also stumbled upon the fact that the building with its pillars even interfered with the public sidewalk.
However, there were no more changes, quite the opposite - just fifteen days after the district's request for this, Josep Batlló filed a request for approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor was a social lounge, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
But Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably without having to relinquish some intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new facade, Gaudí’s renovation also gave the house a rather unusual roof and two more floors.
Gaudí’s play with the light is also impressive, as are the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is covered and the lighthouses.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor is the most spacious and magnificent apartment opened to the public.
It was only in the year that the owners decided to take this step on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were maintained, and they were also extended to other common rooms and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards receive a 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the residents and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed grid? Women have different wishes than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface - so mattress and rust make the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
Many things play a role in the selection - the weight, the size, the state of health and last but not least the sex of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior, in which mattress and rust have to be subordinate.
A typical example?
In a weekend home where it is not heated regularly, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "get warm."
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned on regularly.
If they do not have enough vent ducts in the core and lie on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: it is not excluded that mould forms under them.
Of course, the choice also plays a role in what you are used to.
Those who have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, will find it difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"Well, all the hockey players who have come back from the NHL have complained to me that they can't sleep properly here anymore."
"For their skinned shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam (memory foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"I recommend these, among other things, also to people with diabetes who suffer from a disturbance of the nervous system, so that they can receive the 'information' from the joints and the skin poorly," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That’s why I bought these mattresses with visco foam (memory foam) for many hockey players years ago, but also for other customers.
"Today, this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses are offered by the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico, among others."
And you don’t necessarily have to be a famous ice hockey player to learn to appreciate the benefits of the visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it clings directly to the warm body.
Nowhere is it pressing, at night you don’t roll around like after a heavy fight.
You just sleep much better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (wound burn).
When choosing the size of the mattress, you should still add the length of the soles of the foot to the height, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Men and women, who are up to 180 cm tall, need a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each sleeper should have at least 90 cm of lying width available, i.e. 180 cm together.
For single beds, for example for singles, 120 to 140 cm are appropriate.
For the sake of comfort and also for potential visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies for the ideal bed width: "When you lie on your back, there should be enough space for the slightly angled arms", advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, the master of the upholstery and room furnishings, who has been devoted to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for years.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own rust and their own mattress, but be careful when shopping, so that the mattresses are equally high.
Otherwise, there is nothing else left but to mount the grids at different heights and that is not possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with spring skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be on the mold layer and the fine cushion.
"With your hand or when you sit down, you must not feel the feathers under any circumstances," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a special rust type.
Fully upholstered beds with mattress and base like grown together Siamese twins have nothing to look for in the bedroom.
These mattresses can not be ventilated and the cover can not be washed, which is already common today.
And since you lose between 0.2 to 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged) sieve.
For this reason, experts reject advertising slogans that promise a lifetime of up to 25 years, even a lifetime warranty, for mattresses.
Every thing has its ifs and buts.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: with mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, one should not shy away from the hygiene of washable, removable covers, yet it is recommended to use a mattress protector, which can be easily removed and washed.
Even though today mattress covers are usually made with an all-round zipper, so that you get two halves after opening (immensely important for the washing process and the washing machine size!), manipulation with larger mattresses, especially performed alone, often seems like the unequal battle between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in the bed instead of a grate?
Get out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Even so, they should prefer to provide the plate with ventilation holes (if there are no in it already) and use mattresses with spring skeleton and 15 cm minimum height with so-called pocket spring core and fine padding.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a base.
Latex or sandwich mattresses (possibly also combinations of latex and coconut) are suitable for non-adjustable slatted frames with 14 to 18 slats (slats), always paying off grates with a larger number of slats, i.e. from 28 and more slats, with lumbar support in the lumbar area and the possibility of regulating the slat hardness.
Adjustable lamellar gratings do not include spring skeleton mattresses, as they do not respond to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special fastening of the spring strips, which makes it possible to press in the spring strips or even to bend them in such a way that they allow the shoulder of the sleeper to sink in a point-by-point manner.
Especially for men with wide shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have started to use soft zones for the shoulder area in "men's mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - they are given these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point-elastic wing spring systems (lattoflex) or grates with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multi-torsion suspension are designed.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too large and full) pillow for the right mattress and proper rust, most benefits will be lost again.
Again, a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach up to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Ideally, a 50 x 60 cm cushion appears, as for example the Scandinavians like it.
In the side position, the pillow (together with the shoulder relief zone in the grate or the soft zone in the mattress) should balance the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the former straw bags (filled with hay).
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their admixtures.
Even in mattresses, the new magic word is "organic".
Natural oils – for example castor and soybean oil – are increasingly used instead of petroleum raw materials for the production of polyurethane foams.
Soya is probably used by all known manufacturers.
"Organic means that in mattresses, their core is made of materials of purely natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1>í<0xC4><0x8D>ek of the company Tropico Plus.
However, natural substances are also used in the production of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
However, you can also treat yourself to microcapsules that spread fresh forest or lavender scent while sleeping.
Again, there is a difference between man and woman.
While in men, a "cooling" plant extract from birch leaves is used so that the mattress cover can absorb the heat and cool the body, the covers for women have a "warming" effect.
Extracts of red peppers stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex gets warm during sleep.
And today’s favorites?
Cold foam mattresses (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercial polyurethane and also much more flexible).
The combination of the different stiffness (hardness) of cold foams and visco foams creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hips and heels are located.
For a high-quality mattress, however, you have 7000 crowns and more to charge.
However, health mattresses are usually charged with lower VAT because they are considered medical aids.
Gumotex was the first Czech company to benefit from this advantage.
You see, saving on the mattress and on the rust is not so easy.
From time to time, there are special offers from manufacturers and dealers that offer two mattresses at the price of one.
The Magniflex brand offers the Duofreeze mattress with visco foam memory for 11,990 CZK.
You can get the second one for free.
It was the material Tempur that initiated the era of viscoelastic foams with open cell structure and high density at an almost cosmic pace.
No wonder they were developed for NASA, because the astronauts are exposed to enormous overloads during the launches.
Tempur becomes soft in heat, in a cool environment it solidifies again.
Thus, it adapts perfectly to the human body and distributes the body pressure in an optimal way.
It is therefore not only ideal for preventing pressure burns, but generally increases sleep comfort.
However, viscoelastic foams are not only used in mattresses, but also in other health products, such as special foot cushions, which are intended to provide relief to the legs and vessels.
Local manufacturers use, for example, Eucatherm C foams, Twinsaver or similar products.
