A longer index finger than ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is because it is supposed to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, particularly in men up to sixty,” said Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should absolutely undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health burdens, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the study participants, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the likelihood of prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty-eight percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which already form at prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone in particular accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es, leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told <0xC4><0x8C>TK that he knew about this study but did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be "completely proven".
