The Democratic Routine
The democracy movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil’s influence is greater than that of the United States.
These results came from the Latinobarómetro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year’s September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of democracy advocates rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Such a trend is also evident in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since last year’s sharp downturn.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see diagram 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they are satisfied with their country’s democratic practice, as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
Approximately 34% trust their country’s congress and 45% their government. Both figures are similar to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
The fact that this continued during the Great Depression may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America experienced only a short recession period and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were caught up by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell by 32% again this year.)
However, there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see diagram 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more pronounced and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the start of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see a greater problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see diagram 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they or a family member were victims of a crime in the last year, but compared to 38% in the last year, the figures have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The rising economic output is reflected in the increased support of the private and market economies: about 71% of respondents across the region said that the private sector is essential for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see diagram 6).
Approximately 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private sector), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, nationalized many private companies.
Brazil has the largest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries, on the other hand, see the US as the most influential country, with this role being assumed by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
