Electoral offices opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom were homeless after the January earthquake, roamed around looking for a choice.
Some eventually gave up completely.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected leaders, demanded the suspension of the election results due to an alleged fraud.
There were some violent protests all over the country.
However, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN mission in Haiti, described the election as “pretty good in many respects.”
According to a cautious statement by observers of the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, “these irregularities, however serious they may be, do not necessarily invalidate the process.”
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, allegedly committed to the unpopular outgoing president René Préval and his candidate Jude Célestin, will announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The expected second round is scheduled for January.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial nullity suit.
If Jude Célestin, who receives little or no vote from the electorate, declares that he is the winner of the second round, this could lead to problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million of the earthquake victims still live in tents, low turnout was feared.
On election day, many Haitians were prevented from voting due to a lack of organization.
Shortly before the election began, about 250,000 ID cards required for the election had not yet been issued.
