In the weeks following her husband’s sudden death, Argentina’s president, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that pushed her popularity rate up by 20 points to over 50%, the highest value since her election in 2007.
However, whether you will get this re-election next year depends on whether the apparently grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs of this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who guided economic policy even after his wife’s election, often drafted budgets that did not fully take tax revenues, economic growth and inflation into account.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra revenue at their discretion.
On paper, the Fernández government lost the majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition is divided and Kirchner’s death after a heart attack on October 27 led to further disagreements.
Some regime critics from the ranks of the ruling peronists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
