Arsenic-resistant microbes could enable new forms of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of an alien species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists have discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously deemed vital.
"This organism has two options."
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
“This makes it very special, even though it’s almost a sort of ‘foreign’ form of life,” said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears Thursday in the online issue of Science magazine.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in California’s Mono Lake continues to grow even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“You’re wondering what else is possible,” said Arizona State University co-author Ariel D. Anbar.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists have to recognize life and its forms, says Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were disclosed gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report of the discovery could be about extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "demonstrates that in other planetary systems, organisms can use other elements to initiate biochemical processes, and that the 'standard elements' that we believe are absolutely vital are not necessarily predetermined," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures, one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, they assumed that microbes exposed to both may be able to replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is primarily due to its chemical similarity to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently from phosphorus. It enters our biochemical system, where it smears almost everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic, and it adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, the fact that it can survive in arsenic also shows that an arsenic-based lifeform can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but there hasn’t been a working example yet.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, which is why science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than in the early Earth age," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
