Police operations in China are getting softer
Like a training officer, Tang Shenbin walked over an urban square, checked his nervous subordinates, giving orders with military authority and muted voice.
He wanted his female members of the Chengguan – China’s robust guardians of the urban order, feared and despised for their arbitrary raids and their propensity to violence – to impress viewers.
“Just stand up!”
"Look straight ahead!"
"Show them," he whispered, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls, barely older than teenagers, with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and trousers stood tight.
Four pairs of black pumps were in a straight line.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair held with blue and white striped bows.
"They look average to me," Mr. Tang remarks insignificantly.
"Models are pretty."
Several governments have already tried to polish the image of China’s city inspectors.
In a city, all new applicants must have a university degree.
The province of Guangdong introduced a glowing blue uniform instead of the grey-green one.
Wuhan in central China replaced violence with low staring: In 2009, 50 officials reportedly circled around an improperly positioned snack car and stared at the operator until he packed up after half an hour and left the square.
Xindu, a district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, wants to fundamentally change the image.
Since 2003, 13 women have been reinforcing the urban police strips and have been selected specially for their appearance, good figure and youth.
They should give the brutal police a softer, feminine aspect.
But unfortunately, Scarlett Johansson would hardly succeed in improving the poor image that the Chinese have of these city commands.
Rightly so, the critics.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce municipal laws by means of fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media routinely show a different picture.
In January 2008, officials in Hubei province beat a spectator to death as he filmed them with his cell phone striking down a protest against a dump.
Last year, a training manual of Beijing officials was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how criminals can be beaten without bloodshed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon dealer suffered brain injuries after a clash with five officials.
A video game brimming with violence that can be downloaded from the internet shows Chinese-trained officials in an attack on street traders.
"Chengguan scares the government," the national newspaper China Daily lamented last year, after further controversy over the tactics.
The newspaper called for a “really thorough cleansing.”
Skeptics consider the current approach to be clearly inadequate.
When the district searched for eight female recruits by advertisement in October, an editorial in the Beijing Evening News asked whether the women should have real tasks or only serve as an optical distraction.
Probably both.
According to the job advertisement, women aged 18 to 22 with good figure and "harmonic facial features" were searched.
They should be above average size - over 1.5m or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
The employment relationship ends on reaching the age of 26.
According to the officials, the activity is too physically exhausting for women over 25.
“The most important thing is their image,” an unnamed district official told the government website Rednet.com.
"Whether the candidates get the job depends first on their outward appearance, such as height, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes temperament and "inner qualities".
"Female Chengguans are like flower vases," he said, adding, "but beyond that, they have other duties."
Zheng Lihua, Deputy Head of District City Administration, does not agree with this description,
But admitted that in China, size specifications in job advertisements are not uncommon for both sexes.
The same goes for uniform facial features.
Whether this is equivalent to good looks is controversial in China.
But people with disabilities or physical disfigurements do not need to apply.
"Unfortunately, we can't use lame ones or buckling ones here," says Mr. Zheng.
"Your image would not be good."
Liu Yi, who patrols in Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22, has apple pastry and a well-shaped mouth.
She did not feel sexist that such importance was placed on her appearance.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asks with an ironic look.
Her co-worker with the dimples, 21-year-old Xu Yang, commented, "We have the task of representing the image of the city."
According to them, they do not regret the brief hiring, as they have more ambitious career plans than just shoving traders through the alleys to prevent them from doing business.
Every morning, the squad deals with about twelve street traders who try to sell as many buns and tofu dishes as possible on foot or by bike before they are chased away.
"Mr. Wang, please get out of here."
"We've told you that so many times!" explains Fr. Xu to a dealer who had fled on foot and had temporarily abandoned his pasta kitchen attached to a bicycle cart.
According to the officials, the activity is more monotonous than strenuous.
"It's almost the same every day," explains Huang Jing, 20, who studies in leisure sales.
"Everything routine."
One reason for this is that the female officials are not allowed to confiscate the merchandise of the merchants, like their male counterparts.
They can only threaten offenders to report them to their male superiors.
This is to protect them from public hostilities, which officials in China are often exposed to.
This year, hundreds of residents of Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, ransacked after rumors circulated that Chengguan officials had killed a merchant.
More than a dozen police officers and Chenguan officials were injured in the night incident, 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
Xindu has been spared from such violence so far.
But unrest cannot be ruled out.
Just two blocks away from the quiet Baonguang Square, where the female officials were patrolling that morning, over 50 people gathered at a street corner.
Officials had confiscated a motorcycle that was unlawfully repaired on the sidewalk instead of in a workshop.
The owner shouted Zeter and Mordio.
After 15 minutes of hesitation, the officers with a grim face made their way to their vehicles and drove away with the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, a 40-year-old male coordinator, was left behind, turning his white nameplate to remain anonymous.
Like their colleagues, the coordinators – men over 40 – play a purely supportive role.
But they were not trained to present a clean image.
“Sometimes we go verbally.”
"Sometimes physically," explains Mr. Li soberly.
“Most of the time, people start arguing.”
