Prosecutors at the Department of Justice have acquitted Senator John Ensign of the accusations made against him after his affair with a former electoral assistant and his attempt to get her husband to lobby, Senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday.
This decision puts an end to the most serious accusation against Senator Ensign, the Republican from Nevada, and until the scandal that made headlines nationwide and dampened his career, he was considered a potential Republican presidential candidate for 2012.
As Senator Ensign's office announced, he was "highly delighted" with the verdict after the one-year inquiry.
However, the Senate Ethics Committee could still impose a disciplinary penalty.
According to Ensign’s lawyers, they were informed by the Department of Justice that the investigations against Senator Ensign had been terminated and that there were no further charges in this matter.
The Justice Department did not want to comment on the case.
The verdict was a surprise for many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, and they believe there was sufficient evidence that Ensign disregarded the lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails, and other documents first published in the New York Times in October 2009 gave rise to the assumption that Ensign Douglas Hampton, one of his electoral assistants, was too lucrative to buy his silence over an affair with Hampton's wife Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton served as treasurer during an election campaign for Ensigns.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton work, and according to the documents and interrogations, he took over Hampton's lobbying for them after hiring.
As Hampton was recently on Ensign’s electoral team, he was not allowed to lobby for his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called ban on revolving door lobbying.
According to the published evidence, “it seems to be a collusion and a violation of the revolving door statutes,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney specializing in the defense of clients targeted by the government.
While the Justice Department formally declined to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other Ethican lawyers said the ministry seemed very cautious in picking up political charges following a variety of defeats pursued by the media with great interest, including last year’s decision to drop the charges against former Senator Ted Stevens for misconduct on the part of the state attorney.
Prosecutors “are obviously terrifying,” said Melanie Sloan, the chairwoman of the association “Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington” (an organization whose goal is to fight corruption in U.S. parliamentary and government circles), a group of lawyers who have brought various charges against Mr. Ensign to court.
"This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, chief defender of Mr. Ensign, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another the next day informing him that the ministry would not file any lawsuits against his client.
Mr. Ensign’s defense attorneys had cooperated with the prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, had “acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins declined to explain in more detail the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of the conversation between the Ministry of Justice and me, but I think we've made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to close the investigation on a separate lawsuit by the ethics group, according to which a $96,000 payment from Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated the federal election law.
The Electoral Commission said there was not enough evidence that the money was something other than a gift.
NV Energy, a large Nevada company that long supported the Senator, was one of the companies where Mr. Hampton found lobbyist work thanks to the help of Mr. Ensign.
An email from December 2008 proves that after the company moved on to Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensing's chief of staff, John Lopez, had an interview with Mr. Hampton, in which he told him that he was "knocking" at the Department of the Interior for a matter.
Mr. Ensign was also having lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transport to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline, after it had stopped Mr. Hampton for lobbying.
When information about this affair first came to the public last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his voters and resigned his position in the Senate, where he was fourth in the Republican ranks.
After not being noticed for many months, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he was seeking a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign will no longer be the target of police investigations, his press spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hopes that the Ethics Commission will quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and stop its investigation.
"Senator Ensign is looking forward to continuing its hard work at the service of the people of Nevada," she said.
