Can courtesy connect the dividing?
After a campaign of slander and negativity, little politeness has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before one quickly returns to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and tops of Congress did not bring a breakthrough in the big issues to be dealt with during the so-called "lame duck session", the meeting at the end of a government period in which no decisions are made.
According to all that one hears, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor an observation of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partisan point-gathering.
The president’s public meeting on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that continue to exist between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to separate members from each other.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one of the other demands signs of cooperation and compromise willingness, while trying to weigh the boundaries of public opinion and the patience of the voters after a renewed party warfare.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it is about taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles away from each other.
Last but not least, the November election in Washington voted mildly for at least a short time.
“No question, the tone of voice has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after elections.
Elections awaken party passions that are dying again.
And that's good."
On some issues, especially those that are on the agenda of the "lame duck session," Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution."
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one advocates that.
Both sides want to find a way to receive some or all, whether temporarily or permanently.
Likewise, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich while refusing to support unemployed workers.
After the meeting in the White House on Tuesday, the optimism has increased that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and simultaneously ratify the New START Treaty.
However, William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that a successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session" will not necessarily lead to a lasting cooperation of the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation," he said.
Wehner is also skeptical – and this skepticism is shared by many – that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
“I see a lot of what is happening from today until 2012, as a prelude, or shadow boxing, to the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who helped to form them.
No matter how concerned the Republican leaders may be about poker being too high, they know that they must try to keep their promises of lowering government spending and overturning health care reform.
These party lines are already clear in the initial responses to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as raising the retirement age and lowering government spending.
Deputy Chairman Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have pushed so much to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan the official recommendation and they are struggling very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the body, because in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromises.
Galston predicts two stages in the battle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place in the form of party clashes next year, when Republicans challenge Obama in terms of state budget, taxes, and health care system, later followed by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as it did in 1995, then both parties must pay close attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and the Congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a pure prelude to a far more far-reaching election in 2012.
In this way, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the issues that still separate the two.
Leaked US document portrays Moscow as a port of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of the "cleptocracy" and it passes on part of the bribes and the protection money it collects to the Kremlin, as reported by the American embassy in Russia in a memo in February.
Both the police and the State Security Service are extorting high protection money so that they can maintain their expensive standard of living in Moscow, it is said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal gangs.
Each layer of bureaucracy—what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called “vertical of authority”—takes its share of the money that moves the ladder upwards.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its homepage on Tuesday.
The memo is based on sources whose names have been edited.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still the mayor of Moscow, and it accuses him of corruption.
He was fired by President Dmitry Medvedev in October, but there is hardly any evidence that had been cleaned up in the meantime.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a well-known construction company, have repeatedly rejected allegations of corruption for years, and he has won numerous defamation charges against such allegations.
In September, he explained to a Russian television station when asked about a documentary that suggests he was corrupt: "It's crazy, it's dirty, it's dirty."
> An incredibly large number of Russians believe that their society is corrupt, polls have shown.
But it is unusual that, as happened in the Ambassador's report, individuals are called, and it is unheard of that is done by a diplomat of a foreign country.
"The direct link of the Moscow government to crime has led some to call it 'disturbed' and conclude that the government acts more like a kleptocrat than a government," the memo reads.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'kryshna' (a term from the world of criminals/mafia, which literally means 'roof' or protection) that extends across the police, the State Security (FSB), the Service Supervisory Authority (MVD) and the prosecutor's office as well as the entire Moscow government bureaucracy.
Experts have discovered a three-layered structure within the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"FSB, MVD and the militia are on the second stage."
"Finally, the ordinary criminals and the criminal inspectors follow at the lowest level."
"This is an incompetent system in which criminal groups close a gap in some areas because the city does not offer any help."
The report goes on to say that the FSB is collecting money from the biggest companies and that the police are arresting small businessmen.
One source, it said, "explained that Moscow's business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (and not from organized crime), as they have not only more weapons, resources and power than the criminals, but also because they are protected by law."
“For this reason, protection from criminal gangs is no longer as in demand as it used to be.”
The memo notes that while collecting the funds is comprehensive, the protection itself is not very modest; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who do not pay find their business closed very quickly - due to one or the other pretext.
Medvedev has spoken on several occasions about fighting corruption, but at the same time noted that he has made little progress.
The memo of the embassy contains descriptions of men going to the Kremlin with suitcases that were presumably full of money.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev must rely on the bureaucrats," said Georgy Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow expert commission, in a recent interview.
"But he's part of that bureaucracy."
"It is not part of the political class because a political class no longer exists in Russia."
Without politicians, without opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Nationally, Indem estimates, corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country ranks 154th in a recent study on the global perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are listed from "least corrupt" to "most corrupt").
The revelation of the American embassy memo, which took place late in the evening after Moscow time, will certainly trigger dissatisfaction within the Russian government, although since Luzhkov can be accused of Moscow’s mistakes, it can also be a way for the Kremlin to claim that the problems are solved.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be a fake and responded angry to the revelation that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth is that it's about our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policy in this country," he said.
"But to be honest, we didn't expect this to happen with such arrogance, with such pressure, and in such unethical ways, you know."
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to confront the past
In a dimly lit, concrete classroom with dirty and peeling walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School recalls the man who built it, later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he took care of his people," Sreng Kor Ma, 42, said.
Due to his brutality during Khmer Rouge rule known as "the butcher", the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, longstanding supporters are challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local Truth and Reconciliation Forum allowed the victims to publicly confront the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a textbook that, for the first time, tells children of former soldiers the history of the Khmer Rouge.
And in July, a community tribunal of the UN and Cambodia first sentenced a former member of the Khmer Rouge when it sentenced the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fear grew among Khmer Rouge veterans Alnlong Vengs, making their efforts to reconcile and reintegrate into Cambodia’s society more difficult.
"There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything," said Chhang Youk, head of Cambodia's Documentation Centre, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It divides families itself."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of illness, overwork or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-Ied government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the border of Cambodia to Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement surrendered.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their base in the west of the mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok attracted the next generation in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to overrun into government, leading to the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had not yielded, was arrested by government forces at the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in 2006 in Phnom Penh Prison, where he waited for trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters fled to the excruciating poverty of rural Cambodia and many kept the movement in nostalgic memory.
Even though a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local government posts for laying down their weapons, the ordinary soldiers remained poor, uneducated peasants.
"These people have benefited very little from the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are anchored in the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They grew up without any professional knowledge."
Sor Lim, 55, who had joined the Rhmer Rouge in 1974 as a teenager, fought in the jungle for Anlang Veng before settled in 1998 to live a life as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok has given everyone something to eat."
"But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also raised concerns here.
Earlier next year, the court will try to bring Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, as well as Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court’s mandate is to condemn the old leaders and those who are chiefly responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will pursue further acts beyond these four cases.
This has done little to alleviate the fears in Anlong Veng.
Current media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who had been district chief in Manteay Meanchey Province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told representatives of the Cambodian Documentation Centre that she was in charge of the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced labourers were believed to have died.
On a hot evening, Im Chaem returned from work in the fields to her wooden house on a dirty road outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun threw long shadows on the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss their past at the Khmer Rouge.
Should the court summon her, she would refuse to leave, she said.
"Cambodia lives in peace and stability," she said.
“If there were no more persecutions, there would be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that if the situation became uncertain, the court would indict more suspects, although experts and historians are discussing this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But confrontation with the past is what Cambodia needs to do in order to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center.
“Reconciliation with the Khmer era means bringing together the broken pieces,” he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken parts together so that we can understand everything."
The center created the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia".
It distributed the book in June in Anlong Veng as an appendix to the history book for the Ministry of Education High School, which contains less than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
As often as in Cambodia, the young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helps students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents were skeptical when he brought the book home to read it.
