The manager assumes that Spain would only “slowly” get out of the crisis.
In addition, it would be "very difficult" to "create work" in two or three years - fundamental to the survival of the banks.
Even if he assumes that the war on liabilities - which penalizes interest margins - will diminish, the risk surcharges that banks and savings banks have to pay for their issues to maintain liquidity will already be diverted to the price of loans as a compensation for dwindling profit margins.
"The issues of liquidity and financing are structural and they will put pressure on the loans."
"We haven't turned the rooster off, but the interest rate differentials are very high," Guardiola admitted.
Banesto issued an order to its branch network on Thursday to restrict the issuance of long-term loans and increase interest rate differentials (see Cinco Días of November 22 and 27).
The manager also admitted that the banks were currently pursuing the strategy of "increasing fees", but "within a competitive framework".
Sabadell’s guiding principle is based on organic growth, even though, as always, the group does not exclude corporate business.
It is not for nothing that he assures that in Spain "larger companies are needed."
“Everything will change next year,” he said.
He stresses that the demand for capital is currently "increasing enormously" and does not exclude that some Spanish financial institutions will slip into red figures.
He believes that the FROB can replace the money market in the case of capital stocks.
After reassuring that Sabadell could survive a temporary market closure, he refutes the argument of some bankers who are already prophesying a new liquidity crisis.
