Zapatero and the Red Line of Germany
Berlin has opted for the retention of the euro, but at the same time set conditions for the entire European Union.
Tensions in the markets have triggered a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has proposed new adjustment measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro-enterprises, the regulation of temporary employment companies or the cancellation of the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>426 support for the unemployed who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatization of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of the airports of Barajas and El Prat, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for evoking the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It should be foreseen that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany is taking on a fundamentally new perspective for shaping our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of most of its partners.
Given the resistance in Europe, Germany is starting to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the South would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the reintroduction of the German mark - although this currently sounds more like science fiction - supported by a large part of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a restructuring of the euro in line with German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict financial management; punishing the countries that violate the requirements; possibly the cessation of payments by some countries and the expansion of the costs of potential adaptation measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent this from happening in 2016.
This was the first sign of the divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
At the time, this was heavily criticised, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the public opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel came out with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union agreements in order to enable the rescue of a country while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European as it pushed forward the Irish crisis and everything that followed.
In the coming months, we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will allow these measures to take effect from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old way of working of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the year of the birth of a new monetary area, in which the infringing countries may be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and, in this case, the private sector will have to bear some of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to pursue a tough growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge gaps in the balance of payments, as was mentioned by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would be bad at not understanding it.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil will pass into more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in its own house has made its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like it would change anything.
Among the options considered is the fact that we would have to leave the euro area, which is filled with few serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it had warned us.
Sport and rule circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show ingenuity, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against the Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being shed on whether or not it was an anti-sporting act and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed penalty at the next league match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, UEFA's disciplinary committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos – the unwritten but followed rules in this sport.
Part of the emerging debate around the presented case stems from a team of Real Madrid football club (who in his anthem professed generosity and honor and on other occasions had punished his players for similar incidents) playing the leading role, and from the dramatization by Mourinho, who added one episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this practice, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts constitute an circumvention of rules. In fact, this practice adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sporting spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the offending players from taking an unjustified advantage from the opposing team. Neither did that.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we usually understand by cheating or circumvention, because the rule was not secretly circumvented to avoid a sanction, but it should be as striking as possible so that it will be punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders got from the deliberate fouls.
It should be noted here that the rival was neither put in a less favourable position nor demanded advantages for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, to a certain extent uncertain, as the team could also be eliminated at some point, and players will also receive a sanction and move into the second card cycle, where they will be eliminated less than in the first cycle because of card accumulation with one card.
It is not clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not against the sporting spirit, which also includes strategic decisions in order to get the most out of the regulations.
In this case, players didn’t want to circumvent a sanction (this would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they were more likely to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or escaping from punishment.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and regulatory environment is blurred, I believe this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemic came about as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transfer.
The harm inflicted on the principles of sport by these acts is less ethical than aesthetic.
