The 188 Interpol countries are instructed to identify and locate Assange “to arrest and extradite him provisionally.”
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red warning, many member states, according to the organization, consider the red warning to be a freeze for an arrest — which must be carried out by the national police — especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case of Sweden and England, where Assange is likely to be staying.
The action outraged Assange’s lawyers, who yesterday published a letter informing them that the 39-year-old founder of Wikileaks is ready to answer questions from the Swedish authorities via videoconference.
