China maintains its greenhouse gas reduction targets
China’s representative stated at COP16 that its country has made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and it would maintain its offer to cut 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China is keeping its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16, assures.
At his first public appearance at the United Nations’ 16th World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and convert its industry.
He stated that over the past four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work with the international community on this matter.
He explained that China’s climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption last year of a new energy law that includes targets for reducing emissions of gases, he said.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, the state authorities had worked with those of the central government and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, effective use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he pointed out that several multi-year plans have already been undertaken or completed, both those funded by the Chinese government and those receiving funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Effective Use of Energy Program, which was introduced over the last five years and had received investment from the United Nations (UN), the government and private hands.
There is also a provincial-level project on climate change, another to replace traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another on mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, the country’s climate change scientific government advisor, confirmed that China’s efforts are far greater than is commonly believed.
He pointed out that per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China amount to six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a 9% total contribution to pollution.
The energy efficiency has been increased by 20 percent over the last five years and is expected to be increased by 2020, he said.
