The U.S. changes the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must present themselves to the consulate before their interview with the visa application services; costs will be reduced waiting times.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa in the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves in the consulate to the visa application services (ASC, the initial letters in English) before their interview.
The staff of the ASC records the biometric data of the applicant, which is checked by the consulate before the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa decreases, because it is no longer necessary to pay the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed out separately.
The applicant makes only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counter value is $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for dealers and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not have to have a conversation in the consulate, they only have to present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
Since the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the interview in the consulate will remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the service surcharge of $ 26.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
