Global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew home, trade and industry lighting in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (HFC) that corresponds to nearly a third of the additional reduction that needs to be implemented to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete large-scale projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments by developed countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of CFCs released due to illumination to the earth would be avoided if the white-glowing bulbs, which are still a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better yet, by LEDs.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the global fleet of exhaust gases.
In Copenhagen last year, major exhaust emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, pledged voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, it would still be necessary to deduct 5 Gt from this balance sheet to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020, in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-glowing pears 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice again.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company, by the way, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-glowing bulb, which conveys an indication of the savings of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that completely new kinds of incandescent bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a regulating resistance.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they therefore have to be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the producers provide a pick-up point.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit substantially more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report describes in detail the profits that each country would generate thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year on electricity purchases and 8 million tons of CO2, an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
