Vengeful hackers and busy spies
WikiLeaks has a double meaning.
On the one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between the states, the citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, giving a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's go one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (an x-any nation) is composed exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits are nothing more than what has been read in any X-journal (except for those owned by Berlusconi) over months, and Gaddafi’s terribly caricatured profile has long provided cabaret artists with material for their sketches.
The rule that the secret files may consist only of known news is essential to the dynamism of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that every work (about the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rose-Cross-Cross) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (neither because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe in nothing but what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown’s success mechanism.
Same with the secret records.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited spirit) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be whatever, for example, editor at Libération), who only considers what he acknowledges to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why was such a fuss made about the revelations of these dossiers?
On the one hand, these state what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies – at least since the end of World War II and since then the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner – have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some small representation tasks, have turned into espionage centers.
Any viewer of investigative movies knows this very well, and it is not by hypocrisy that one acts to ignore this.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that an x-any hacker can tap into the most secrets of the most powerful country in the world carries the significant blow against the prestige of the State Department.
In addition, the scandal brings less the victims, but rather the "sharpeners" in trouble.
But let us dedicate ourselves to the profound nature of what happened.
Once, in Orwell’s time, you could bundle all power like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy could have proven to be perfectly correct since then, where you can control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the chosen highway and so on; the citizen would become a total victim of the eye of power.
But if one considers what is happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control channel ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – chosen as a vengeance of the citizen – can discover the secrets of power.
But how can a power keep itself that is no longer able to keep its own secrets?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of Berlusconi’s or Merkel’s character is basically a secret free of secrets, as it reveals the public sphere; but to disclose in the style of WikiLeaks, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets to power, means to steal.
WikiLeaks has not wronged Sarkozy or Merkel, but Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this insult inflicted on such a mighty power?
It is obvious that in the future, the states will no longer put any reserved information online - that would be like a sticker on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with the latest technologies, it is in vain to hope to be able to keep confidential reports over the phone secret.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a head of state moved on an airplane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships be maintained in the future and only for certain ears?
I know very well that my prediction sounds science-fiction and novel at the moment, but I am compelled to imagine the government agents moving secretly on uncontrollable march routes, carrying their messages nowhere else but in mere memory, and hiding the few written information they have received, in the shoe set.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, Watergate’s spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is progressing like a cancer nowadays, namely backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet reconstructs a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analog) video cassettes had allowed the film researchers to explore a film tape by tape, by rewinding from the back to the front and uncovering all the secrets of the assembly, while the (numeric) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro portions.
With high-speed trains you can travel from Rome to Milan within three hours, while this takes three and a half hours by plane, including the changeover.
It is therefore not unusual that politics and communication technology come back to cars and horses.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: How France is talking about its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine compliance with the fast-resolved financing promises (also called "fast start" or premature financing) realised by developing countries.
And now the rough French fairy tales have been uncovered.
Under the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries pledged to allocate $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years, France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU has drawn up all the registers to convince its partners of its commitment to fast-start funding: detailed action report from its Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and appreciated for its true value: developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announced it had released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to pay respect to its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look into the details, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" in order to ensure that an additional contribution has been made without being made to the detriment of public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what “new and additional” means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the guideline that they deem best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen itself as a benchmark for 2009: international financing will be retained and 150 million will be added to the Fast Start funding for over three years.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or in terms of conditions at the level of public development aid.
In return, France felt that the financing of “all new projects” of 2010 were “new and additional.”
In other words, there are no benchmarks for the expenditure of the previous year or at the global level of public development aid.
Specifically, the total amount of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France pretends to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses their computing mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed as equivalent to 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> donated.
Obviously, this is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often emission control projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro collected as the equivalent of a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan to the investor country should be credited as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent rate of an interest).
But France has nothing other than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% (36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) carry out 100% of their commitments with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to fulfil its obligations, France gives just 10 cents and understands a comparable stake.
Nice hocus pocus!
All in all, France’s fast-start financing is operating with a double fraud: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of financial stakes.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Treasury (as it seems that it was Bercy who conducted the arbitration) could have a double negative effect; once within the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter of early financing is only a small question on a relatively short period of time compared to the whole of discussions about the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn the lesson from this first year of early financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its accounting style for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and balanced justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward the discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another, crucial and currently debated issue): one does not escape the question of "accountability" or the way in which his loans are accounted for.
France could change its position to be as progressive on the issues as it is on other matters.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement of France's fast-start and its vision of "accountability" and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old child takes 81 different chemical substances during the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association Générations Futures (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its findings "do not reflect statistically significant value given the small number of samples analyzed, but represent an illustrative nature of the problem dealt with," had bought between July and September the foods commonly consumed within four meals by about a ten-year-old child plus a snack in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals – including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit sections, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day – were studied as well as snacks from laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is devastating: 81 chemical substances, including 42 potentially or likely to be carcinogenic and five safely carcinogenic, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disturbance, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical individually ingested substance are not exceeded in the approximate totality of cases, this survey shows very well that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine disruptors is alarming," notes the association.
At breakfast alone, butter and tea with milk already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three have proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for the green beans from Kenya, including lunch, in which the study found traces of a strictly prohibited insecticide in the EU.
In addition, the hack steak, the tuna from the can, even the baguette and chewing gum of pesticides and other chemicals were spiked.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 chemical residues determined was the "most rich", and even the plastic plate used to warm the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The ultimate risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer "is likely to be underestimated," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in view of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in civilization diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) had identified references to the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
